# pvtest --devices manifest (single real device).
#
#   ./test.docker.sh run <test> --devices devices.txt        # run the suite on the device
#   ./test.docker.sh run <test> -i --devices devices.txt     # open the tester console on it
#
# Exactly ONE device stanza is allowed (more than one is a hard error). The tester
# reaches the device over exec= (becomes PVTEST_EXEC, used to run pvcontrol/pventer)
# and ip= (becomes PVTEST_HOST, used for the pvr HTTP endpoint at
# http://<ip>:12368/cgi-bin/pvr). Tests whose setup.required-config the live device
# does not already satisfy are SKIPPED (a device's config can't be injected the way
# an appengine container's is). See docs/testing/device-target.md.
#
# Fields (blank-line-separated key=value; '#' lines are comments):
#   name=  slot/log name; the run's serial console capture is appengine-<name>.log
#   ip=    device IP for pvr HTTP calls            -> PVTEST_HOST
#   exec=  command prefix to run commands on it    -> PVTEST_EXEC
#   tty=   host-local serial console device path (read directly for the console log)
#   baud=  optional serial baud rate (default 115200)
#
# Prefer stable /dev/serial/by-id/... symlinks over raw /dev/ttyUSBN (USB
# enumeration order isn't stable across host reboots). Copy this file, fill in your
# device's ip/exec/tty, and drop the leading '#' below.

#name=m2-01
#ip=192.168.1.50
#exec=ssh -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no -o UserKnownHostsFile=/dev/null -o LogLevel=ERROR -i /keys/m2.pem root@192.168.1.50
#tty=/dev/serial/by-id/usb-FTDI_FT232R_USB_UART-if00-port0
#baud=115200
